Imagine you are looking at a large, generic basket on a table. The sign on the table says "Fruit Basket: Any Fruit Welcome." Naturally, 
you assume you can put any type of fruit in there. However, what you don't know is that on the bottom of the basket, there is a permanent, 
hidden manufacturing label that says: "Strictly for Apples Only." You walk up with an Orange and try to put it in the basket. Even though 
an Orange is a fruit (and technically fits the "Fruit Basket" sign on the table), the basket itself rejects the Orange because its true, 
underlying physical form was specifically manufactured to only hold Apples. In the C# world, the basket rejecting your Orange because the 
types don't match its true identity is exactly what an ArrayTypeMismatchException is. 

## The Technical Reality

In C#, arrays have a feature (often considered a historical design flaw) called Array Covariance. Because every string is technically an object, 
C# allows you to take a string[] (an array of strings) and assign it to an object[] (an array of objects) variable. However, changing the variable 
reference does not change the actual array in memory. The array in memory is still strictly a string[]. It is just wearing an object[] disguise.
If you try to use that object[] disguise to sneak an integer (like 100) into the array, the .NET runtime looks at the actual memory structure, 
realizes it only has room for strings, and throws an ArrayTypeMismatchException to prevent memory corruption.

## Let's Look at the Code

// STEP 1: We define an array that specifically holds text (strings). 
// This is our "Apple Basket".
string[] languages = { "C#", "Java" };

// STEP 2: We assign this array to a reference of type 'object[]'.
// Because every string is an object, the compiler allows this disguise.
// But beware! Deep down in memory, this is still strictly a "string array".
object[] objects = languages; 

// STEP 3: THE BOOM! (ArrayTypeMismatchException)
// Here, we try to put an integer (100) into objects[0]. (Trying to put an Orange in!)
// The runtime looks at the actual array in memory and says: 
// "Your true identity is a string array, you cannot hold an integer!"
// The program crashes right here.
objects[0] = 100;
